The spline thing

Kenny Ye

One of the reviewers made the following comments on the original manuscript Apparent threshold for dose-response relationship - It ispleasing to see a dose-response relationship between pack-years of smoking and mutation burden. The authors claim of a threshold at which this relationship ceases is less convincing. Presumably this is a post hoc analysis (ie defined after seeing the data, rather than specified a priori) - in which case it suffers the risk of inflated type 1 error rates (and should therefore require a more stringent p value). The grid search methodology for the optimal threshold in particular would seem prone to such inflation - a better approach would be to fit a cubic spline to the relationship as an exploratory tool; test whether the spline fit is better than the linear fit; and show confidence intervals plus fitted curve for the spline in the figure.

Theoretially, the B-spline can be incorporated into generalized linear model. A cubic spline for B-spline is order 4 with a number of knots that satistifies, nbasis = norder + nknots - 2. A piecewise linear model is equivalent to a order 2 B-spline with 1 knot. And our change point model is a special case of order-2 B-spline with a non-fixed knot, and a second segment being flat.

Here we will incorporate the regular 2-degree B-spline with no restriction.

### Order-4 Bspline, Cubic with one knot by default in the middle There is little

    data = SNVa)

dev.o4 <- -as.numeric(summary(glm.spline)$twologlik)

general piecewise linear model using B-spline

x <- SNVa$Smoking_pack_year
dev <- c()
for (tau in seq(5, 115, 1)) {
    bs <- create.bspline.basis(c(0, 116), nbasis = 3, norder = 2, breaks = c(0, tau, 
        116))
    glm.fit <- glm.nb(SNV_observed ~ Age + eval.basis(x, bs) - 1 + offset(log(surveyed_genome_adjusted)), 
        data = SNVa)
    dev <- c(dev, -glm.fit$twologlik)
}

plot(dev)
abline(h = dev0)
abline(h = dev1)

### the best change point
tau.hat <- seq(5, 115, 1)[which.min(dev)]
tau.hat
## [1] 26
dev2 <- min(dev)

mutations.a <- subset(mutations,Individual!="Bulk1320")

plot(mutations.a$Smoking_pack_year, mutations.a$SNV_perCell,log="y",xlab="Smoking pack years",ylab="estimated SNV mutations") 

bs <- create.bspline.basis(c(0,116),nbasis=5,norder=4)
wgl <- mean((mutations$SNV_surveyed_genome*mutations$SNV_sensitivity)/(mutations$SNV_observed/mutations$SNV_perCell))
m.age <- exp(mean(log(SNVa$Age)))

### estimate of the fixed effects
bhat <- coef(glmer.spline)$Individual[1,2:7]
### design matrix
XX <- cbind(m.age-40,eval.basis(bs,0:116))

lines(0:116,wgl*exp(XX %*% t(bhat)),lty=1,col=3)

x.a <- 0:116
x.a[x.a > tau.hat] <- tau.hat
b <- apply(coef(glmer1a)$Individual,2,mean)

linear.threshold.fits <- wgl*exp(b[1]+x.a * b[3]  + b[2]*(m.age-40))

lines(0:116,linear.threshold.fits,lty=1,col=4)

Confidence Interval for Spline

Let \(\hat{\beta}\) be the coefficients of the B-spline basis, given the covariance matrix of \(\hat{\beta}\), we have \(var(a'\hat{\beta}) = a' var(\hat{\beta}) a\). From the standard error, we can obtain a confidence interval from the normal approximation.

### covariance matrix

W <- summary(glmer.spline)$vcov

se <- sqrt(diag(XX %*% W %*% t(XX)))

mm <- XX %*% t(bhat)
upper <- wgl*exp(1.96*se + mm)
lower <- wgl*exp(-1.96*se + mm)

plot(mutations.a$Smoking_pack_year, mutations.a$SNV_perCell,log="y",xlab="Smoking pack years",ylab="estimated SNV mutations") 
lines(0:116,wgl*exp(XX %*% t(bhat)),lty=1,col=3)
lines(0:116,upper,lty=2,col=3)
lines(0:116,lower,lty=2,col=3)
lines(0:116,linear.threshold.fits,lty=1,col=4)

Export data for plots

linePlots <- data.frame(0:116, wgl * exp(mm), lower, upper, linear.threshold.fits)
names(linePlots) <- c("pack_years", "spline", "spline.lower", "spline.upper", "linear_threshold")
write.csv(linePlots, file = "model_fits.csv", quote = F, row.names = F)
